06003nam a22007695i 9781438482392DE-B159720240307104700.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240307t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384823927 a10.1515/97814384823922doi  a(DE-B1597)683368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHM671b.M346 2021 7aPHI0140002bisacsh04a303.3/7222300aMaking the Case :bFeminist and Critical Race Philosophers Engage Case Studies /ced. by Nancy Arden McHugh, Heidi Grasswick. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (360 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tTheoretical and Methodological Perspectives on Case Studies -- tBuilding a Case for Social Justice Situated Case Studies in Nonideal Social Theory -- tThe Coupled Ethical-Epistemic Model as a Resource for Feminist Philosophy of Science, and a Case Study Applying the Model to the Demography of Hispanic Identity -- tFeminist Science Studies Reasoning from Cases -- tCritiquing The Practice: The Case of Philosophy -- tThe Power and Perils of Example -- tWhat Philosophy Does (Not) Know -- tDoing Things with Case Studies -- tCase Studies for Social Justice -- tSinging the “Blues” for Black Male Bodies Epistemic Violence, Non-alterity, and Black-Male Killings -- tLand(point) Epistemologies -- tEpistemology and HIV Transmission -- tMestizaje as an Epistemology of Ignorance -- tEpistemic Activism and the Politics of Credibility -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaking the Case brings together established and emerging philosophers who use case studies to address a variety of contemporary social justice causes. The contributors show both the depth and breadth of work in this area and highlight the distinctive approaches that feminist and critical race theorists, in particular, have pursued. For these theorists, the choice of the kinds of cases analyzed matters, not only pushing philosophy as a field to foreground the challenges facing marginalized groups but also affecting the kind of philosophy that results. This ensures that their theories do not reproduce the conceptual frameworks of dominant groups. By using thickly described cases, as opposed to the thinly described or hypothetical situations that have been the historic mainstay of philosophy, the contributors strive to create philosophy that never strays too far from the complexities of people's lives on the ground. The book provides philosophers with a host of methodologies, theories, and practical examples for use in social justice case work, with topics ranging from census design and gender bias in science to incarceration and the spate of recent police killings of black men and women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist theory. 0aRacism. 0aSocial justicevCase studies. 0aSocial justice--Case studies. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Epistemology. 4aPhilosophy : Feminist Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aAragon, Corwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattle, ShaDawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCode, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrasnow, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Lacey J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehr, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallegos-Ordorica, Sergio Armando, econtrib